Do you remember your 6th birthday? Mine was unforgettable. My family went to Aquinnah, saw the brick lighthouse, climbed down the clay cliffs to the beach below. Red, grey, white, and orange clay were a child’s delight! Native Americans dressed in fringed clothing and beaded moccasins offered silver and turquoise jewelry. They were marvelous to me. I remember playing in a puddle of rainwater in the clay on our descent. 

Much has changed. Now buses bring tourists to view a remnant of the lighthouse that had to be moved due to erosion on the cliffs (recorded for a PBS special). No one is allowed to climb on the cliffs anymore. But they are still spectacular. 

I go to the island in my dreams. My grandmother’s cottage was there, the home of my favorite childhood memories.

Time for a few tips…I’m greying down the turquoise and cleaning up the whites because the colors were too competitive and the whites were looking dirty. 
Some process notes: It seemed like the turquoise and pink were competing too much. I like to tone colors down with the opposite color on the wheel and sometimes I use grey paint. Comes in handy. 

Do you have a list of self-critique questions when you paint? I ask if my lights and darks AND warms and cools are balanced. Imbalance creates more interest so I needed to lighten up some darks (or darken some lights) because my piece was too balanced. 

Hope you found this interesting. I’m sure having fun! This piece really makes me happy. I’m calling it “Rhythms of Joy.”

Ask yourself, “Why do I create?” Seriously. Isn’t it okay to let go of the work when it’s finished? Why are our paintings precious? Sure. Lots and lots of work. But isn’t it also about the process? If we set out to make paintings to make money, aren’t we missing the best part? Im thinking about it. Isn’t the process all about expression, passion, peace, facing challenges? 

For me, I want my work to bring peace to viewers. If a painting has served that purpose or even fails, I still own the satisfaction of some very fulfilling studio time. My studio is my sanctuary l, my place of peace and re-centering. 

Can you let go? Get free. Get brave. Get happy. Paint over something that you’re not super happy about. Let’s give ourselves permission to move on and grow.

You know that great big brush that you hardly ever use? Load it up with paint and make some big bold 2023 brush marks! Go ahead, you know you want to. It doesn’t have to be this big. 

Are you worried about wasting expensive paint? Thin it with matte medium and some water. Or buy some Nova or Lukas Cryl in big jars. Paint like a millionaire. Queen for a day. Never look back and think, “I wish I had gone for it, tried that brave daring thing in my art!”

I learned from Robin Williams in her books for graphic designers that if you’re gonna use contrast, make it count. Use super huge elements juxtaposed with delicate touches. Big contrasts are thrilling to create and exciting to see. Think thick-thin, straight-squiggly, huge-tiny. As they say, “go large or go home!” And don’t forget to laugh along the way. You’re gonna be having so much fun!

It helps me avoid the temptation to choke up on the brush if I sketch some guidelines in chalk. The chalk is easily removed with water after the paint dries. 

Observe the light. Sometimes it’s brightest on the farthest side from the light source. The light goes in and bounces off the back of the vase. There’s usually a highlight too and then a prism effect sometimes leaves a hot spot on the table outside the glass. So doggone beautiful and so fun to paint. 

Wanna learn how to draw vases? I teach an easy to understand method in my online course, “Simply Glass.” Now only $100. You also learn about color harmony and how to paint hydrangeas.

Did you know you can thin paint with matte medium or glazing medium to make a transparent layer? Transparent pigments work best for this but any color can be thinned with medium enough to become transparent! Golden paints have black lines on the labels with the paint over them. It’s amazing how fear can sear a memory into the brain. We were kids. Back then we went anywhere without our parents — on our bikes or on foot — exploring. That day we were walking out on a long stone jetty that protected the harbor inlet. Low tide. I was at the waterline, on the exposed algae, checking out the barnacles. Suddenly a crazy guy drove his boat too fast through the no-wake zone and a wave swept over my legs. On that slippery algae I lost my balance and fell into deep water. My cousin saw the whole thing and heroically reacted, extending his arm to rescue me. I’ll bet he has no memory of hoisting me now, but I will never forget. Here’s my abstracted memory of those safe and dry jetty rocks. 

#jetty #rockycoastline #heroicrescue #nowakezone #safeandsecure #blueandwhite #coastalliving #coastaldecor #beachlifevibes #oceanlover #thevineyard

I spend a lot of time visualizing. Looking at color trends. Imagining my happy places of peace. This world wants us in overdrive ALL THE TIME. But if we want to produce thoughtful artwork we owe it to ourselves to find quiet spaces in our lives.

A lot of artists wonder how to tell if a work is finished! As Al Lachman says, “If it feels right it is right.” And the converse is true. Next time you wonder if a piece is finished, ask yourself Al’s question, “Does it feel right?” A lot of you liked the previous blue background on this. I liked it too. But something didn’t quite feel right to me. In fact it started feeling a little underwater, hehe. So I couldn’t leave it there. 

For this final version I painted over the background with my original underpainting color, Pyrole Red. Then I did some scumbling with warm and cool neutrals. Since this is for a show depicting Hope, I chose a dark value so that the whites would pop a little more. 

Just remember that if you do the dreaded thing and overwork or mess something up, you can always repaint. Just take that risk. Keep going until it feels right. You will learn more and like it more if you take risks. 

Time for some varnish and I’m moving on. Woohooo!!!! Thanks, friends, for helping me wade through my doubts.

Here’s a simple technique for achieving color harmony! In this example I used pink as my mother color. I often keep mixing into my previous color as I move through a painting. Another method is to mix a color using all colors on your palette and use that as your mother color. I often use a minimalist palette of 4-6 colors plus white. I’m fascinated by the variety we can get from the muted neutrals that result from just a few colors. I used to worry about ending up with muddy color. Now I celebrate it.

I’m reading a book written by a gallerist for artists called “Starving to Successful” by J. Jason Horeijs. One of his biggest points is that we need to present a professional high-end product. Let’s do this!

The secret to professionally preparing canvas for hanging is plastic coated wire. Say byebye wire ends that pierce your fingertips. And this simple tying method makes a tidy knot that looks like a frame shop did the job. 

I’m preparing some sold canvasses for shipping. I use D hooks screwed to the frame 1/3 from the top. I stretch the wire straight across, but there’s still enough give to hang it easily. I also add bumpers to protect walls, help the piece to hang evenly from the wall, and allow air to circulate behind the canvas. I recently started writing the title and signing on the back of the canvas too. I use a paint pen for that so it won’t bleed through to the front. That’s a wrap! Preparing to paint hydrangeas! It was 92 degrees here yesterday and the car was an oven. By the time I got home these were starting to wilt. I dipped the blossoms in a sink of water, used a clipper to do a fresh clean diagonal cut on each stem, sat them in HOT water for about 10 minutes then into the vase with cut flower powder and room temperature water. They perked up in about an hour. I watched a YouTube video and saw someone soak hydrangea stems and badly wilted flowers in water for 3 hours. They revived! Hydrangeas can drink through their blossoms and that’s why the root of their name is water — hydra as in hydrate.

Packing a 36x36” gallery wrapped canvas for shipping. (Save this for later when you need it!)

- Wrap with cling wrap. This keeps it clean and makes it easier to get the noodles on
- I bought 4 small diameter pool noodles from the dollar store
- Cut two pool noodles a few inches longer than canvas to protect corners. 
- Slit through one wall of the noodles down the length then work them onto two opposite edges of the canvas. It helps to pry the noodles apart a little. 
- Cut two noodles to fit the remaining edges just between the first two. 
- Using insulation sheets from the home improvement store (sold in 6 packs 3/4” x 14.5” x 48”) cut to cover the areas inside the noodles front and back. 
- Use packaging tape to secure their positions.
- Box and ship. I used a four piece adjustable 48”x60” x4” box. The box pieces end up overlapping so there are 4 layers of cardboard protecting the middle of the canvas.

A long time ago — before lighthouses were automated — lighthouse keepers were stationed at the houses to maintain the lights, the brass, the foghorns, the houses and grounds. That was before the internet and cell phones. For those poor souls who were single, and posted at remote lights, it was a lonely life. 

Did you know each lighthouse has a unique light flashing pattern and — in case the light isn’t visible — pattern of foghorn bursts? It identifies location for ships. 

My brother was working on a series of photos for a book. You guessed it…all about lighthouses. I got to tag along. We spent a summer camping and moving from lighthouse to lighthouse in the UK. The keepers were the most hospitable people in the world, as you might imagine. They were starved for company. We were starved for a hot meal and a bath. It worked out well. Except my brother’s beautiful photos, all on 8x10” negatives taken on an old Deordorff view camera, were lost in transit to the photo lab. We were crushed. We hugged each other and wept. But lighthouses are the ultimate symbol of safety and refuge. I’ll always love them.

Working on a demo for my @mastrius.official mentoring group. I love to tape down 6-8 pieces of watercolor paper for quick studies. 

Members of my group are painting florals, deconstructed (abstracted) florals, AND abstracts. That’s right! This is a diverse group. But the principles of great paintings apply to most approaches. Did you know that repetition and variation work together in successful paintings? 

I’ve taught a lot of beginner abstract painting students using a lot of fun approaches. The bottom line is that becoming a good painter in any style takes time and practice. It’s a fun journey…unless we mistakenly think it can be mastered in one session. It’s like planting a garden. A good harvest takes time, cultivation. While we tend that garden we are honing our skills, developing a unique vocabulary of expression. Along the way we discover wonders. 

That’s the joy of painting. Every time we push paint around we are learning. Let’s get those paints out and be patient with ourselves. Have fun and enjoy the journey!

How do you break through when you’re stuck?

You know the story. You set out to create a nice loose painting and the more you work on it, the tighter it gets. It’s a big club. 

I gotta laugh at myself. I kept working and working — painting and repainting these red flowers — until I realized I was getting the same results because I was using THE SAME  tools over and over. Had to get brave and do a major paint over of these red flowers. Picked up a cake decorating wedge instead of a brush and a deeper value than block in some big changes on this 48x48” canvas. 

One of the most empowering things I ever learned is that we should never be afraid to paint over part of a painting. No matter how much we like a section, it may be preventing us from achieving a great composition. Sometimes we need to do something radical to move forward. Don’t hesitate to take risks!
